00:01:03.249 --> 00:01:07.840
So the silk road didn’t begin trade, but
it did radically expand its scope, and the

00:01:07.840 --> 00:01:13.040
connections that were formed by mostly unknown
merchants arguably changed the world more

00:01:13.040 --> 00:01:15.370
than any political or religious leaders.

00:01:15.370 --> 00:01:18.640
It was especially cool If you were rich, because
you finally had something to spend your money

00:01:18.649 --> 00:01:23.539
on other than temples. But even if you weren’t
rich, the Silk Road reshaped the lives of

00:01:23.539 --> 00:01:27.959
everyone living in Africa and Eurasia, as we will
see today. Let’s go straight to the Thought Bubble.

00:01:27.960 --> 00:01:31.859
As previously mentioned, the silk road was
not a road. It’s not like archaeologists

00:01:31.859 --> 00:01:36.009
working in Uzbekistan have uncovered a bunch
of yield signs and baby on board stickers.

00:01:36.009 --> 00:01:39.460
It was an overland route where merchants carried
goods for trade.

00:01:39.460 --> 00:01:44.280
But it was really two routes: One that connected
the Eastern Mediterranean to Central Asia

00:01:44.280 --> 00:01:47.300
and one that went from Central Asia to China.

00:01:47.300 --> 00:01:51.260
Further complicating things, the Silk Road
involved sea routes: Many goods reached Rome

00:01:51.270 --> 00:01:52.600
via the Mediterranean,

00:01:52.600 --> 00:01:57.390
and goods from Central Asia found their way
across the Pacific to Japan and even Java.

00:01:57.390 --> 00:02:01.749
So we shouldn’t think of the Silk Road as
a road but rather as a network of trade routes.

00:02:01.749 --> 00:02:06.079
But just as now, the goods traveled more than
the people who traded them: Very few traders

00:02:06.079 --> 00:02:10.720
traversed the entire silk road: Instead, they’d
move back and forth between towns, selling

00:02:10.720 --> 00:02:15.090
to traders who’d take the goods further
toward their destination, with everybody marking

00:02:15.090 --> 00:02:16.860
up prices along the way.

00:02:16.860 --> 00:02:22.400
So what’d they trade? Well silk, for starters.
For millennia, silk was only produced in China.

00:02:22.400 --> 00:02:27.990
It is spun from the cocoons of mulberry tree-eating
worms and the process of silk making as well

00:02:27.990 --> 00:02:33.010
as the techniques for raising the worms were
closely guarded secrets, since the lion’s

00:02:33.010 --> 00:02:35.500
share of China’s wealth came from silk production.

00:02:35.500 --> 00:02:39.850
The Chinese used silk as fishing line, to
buy off nomadic raiders to keep things peaceful,

00:02:39.850 --> 00:02:41.830
and to write before they invented paper.

00:02:41.830 --> 00:02:46.260
But as an export, silk was mostly used for
clothes: Silk clothing feels light in the

00:02:46.260 --> 00:02:51.480
summer and warm in the winter, and until we
invented $700 pre-distressed designer jeans,

00:02:51.480 --> 00:02:55.960
decking yourself out in silk was the #1 way
to show people that you were wealthy.

00:02:55.960 --> 00:02:58.800
Thanks, Thought Bubble. But the silk road
wasn’t all about silk.

00:02:58.800 --> 00:03:05.380
The Mediterranean exported such cliched goods
as olives, olive oil, wine, and mustachioed plumbers.

00:03:05.380 --> 00:03:09.560
China also exported raw materials like
jade, silver, and iron. India exported

00:03:09.560 --> 00:03:14.040
fine cotton textiles; the ivory that originated
in East Africa made its way across the Silk Road;

00:03:14.040 --> 00:03:18.980
And Arabia exported incense and spices and
tortoise shells. Oh, god, it’s a red one,

00:03:18.990 --> 00:03:21.390
isn’t it? It’s just gonna chase me, I
just--- Ow.

00:03:21.390 --> 00:03:25.220
Up until now on Crash Course we’ve been
focused on city-dwelling civilizational types,

00:03:25.230 --> 00:03:29.320
but with the growth of the silk road, the
nomadic people of Central Asia suddenly become

00:03:29.320 --> 00:03:31.350
much more important to world history.

00:03:31.350 --> 00:03:35.770
Most of Central Asia isn’t great for agriculture,
but it’s difficult to conquer, unless you

00:03:35.770 --> 00:03:38.630
are, wait for it -- The Mongols.

00:03:40.810 --> 00:03:44.960
It also lends itself fairly well to herding,
and since nomads are definitionally good at

00:03:44.960 --> 00:03:50.840
moving around, they’re also good at moving stuff from
Point A to Point B, which makes them good traders.

00:03:50.840 --> 00:03:53.480
Plus all their travel made them more resistant
to diseases.

00:03:53.480 --> 00:03:57.980
One group of such nomads, the Yuezhi, were
humiliated in battle in the 2nd century BCE

00:03:57.980 --> 00:04:03.560
by their bitter rivals the Xiongnu, who turned
the Yuezhi king’s skull into a drinking cup, in fact.

00:04:03.560 --> 00:04:07.680
And in the wake of that the Yuezhi migrated
to Bactria and started the Kushan Empire in

00:04:07.680 --> 00:04:09.660
what is now Afghanistan and Pakistan.

00:04:09.660 --> 00:04:13.440
Although silk road trading began more than
a century before the birth of Jesus, it really took

00:04:13.440 --> 00:04:19.320
off in the second and third centuries CE, and the Kushan
Empire became a huge hub for that silk road trade.

00:04:19.330 --> 00:04:23.000
By then, nomads were being eclipsed by professional
merchants who travelled the silk roads, often

00:04:23.000 --> 00:04:28.920
making huge profits, but those cities that had been
founded by nomadic peoples became hugely important.

00:04:28.920 --> 00:04:32.240
They continued to grow, because most of the
trade on the Silk Road was by caravan, and

00:04:32.240 --> 00:04:36.100
those caravans had to stop frequently, you
know, for like food and water and prostitutes.

00:04:36.100 --> 00:04:40.250
These towns became fantastically wealthy:
One, Palmyra, was particularly important because

00:04:40.250 --> 00:04:44.770
all of the incense and silk that travelled
to Rome had to go through Palmyra.

00:04:44.770 --> 00:04:48.760
Silk was so popular among the Roman elite
that the Roman senate repeatedly tried to ban it,

00:04:48.760 --> 00:04:54.460
complaining about trade imbalances caused by the
silk trade and also that silk was inadequately modest.

00:04:54.460 --> 00:04:59.640
To quote Seneca the Younger, “I see clothes of silk,
if materials that do not hide the body, nor even

00:04:59.640 --> 00:05:02.040
one's decency, can be called clothes,”

00:05:02.050 --> 00:05:06.010
he also said of the woman who wears silk,
“her husband has no more acquaintance than

00:05:06.010 --> 00:05:08.880
any outsider or foreigner with his wife's
body."

00:05:08.880 --> 00:05:12.400
And yet all attempts to ban silk failed,
which speaks to how much,

00:05:12.400 --> 00:05:15.280
even in the ancient world, wealth shaped governance.

00:05:15.280 --> 00:05:19.320
And with trade, there was a way to become
wealthy without being a king or lord who takes

00:05:19.320 --> 00:05:21.020
part of what your citizens produce.

00:05:21.020 --> 00:05:24.580
The merchant class that grew along with the
Silk Road came to have a lot of political

00:05:24.580 --> 00:05:30.080
clout, and in some ways that began the tension that we
still see today between wealth and politics. Whether

00:05:30.080 --> 00:05:36.560
it’s, you know, corporations making large donations
or Vladimir Putin periodically jailing billionaires.

00:05:36.560 --> 00:05:41.100
Mr. Putin, I just want to state for the record that I did
not mean that in any way, I was -- Stan wrote that joke.

